SIMPLE: enfranchise
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enfranchise
<hw>En*fran"chise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Enfranchised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Enfranchising</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Pref. <ets>en-</ets> + <ets>franchise</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>enfranchir</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set free; to liberate
from slavery, prison, or any binding power.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To endow with a franchise; to incorporate into a
body politic and thus to invest with civil and political privileges; to
admit to the privileges of a freeman; to give the right to
vote.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To receive as denizens; to naturalize; <as>as, to
<ex>enfranchise</ex> foreign words</as>.</def> <rj><au>I.
Watts.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>enfranchised</ent>⟦br⟧
